  "footnotes": [
    "Mehrgarh (c.7000–2500 BCE): Located in Balochistan, one of the earliest Neolithic farming sites in the world. Evidence of agriculture, dentistry, and proto-urban development predating the Indus Valley Civilization by 2,000 years.",
    "Indus Valley Civilization (c.3300–1300 BCE): One of the world's three earliest urban civilizations, with sites across modern Pakistan (Mohenjo-daro, Harappa, Ganeriwal, Kot Diji, Amri-Nal). Sophisticated urban planning, drainage systems, standardised weights, and undeciphered script.",
    "Gandhara (c.600 BCE–1000 CE): The northwestern region centred on Taxila and Peshawar. A crossroads of Greek, Persian, Central Asian, and Indian cultures. The Gandhara school of Buddhist art, developed under Kushan patronage, was the first to depict the Buddha in human form.",
    "Muhammad bin Qasim's conquest of Sindh (711–712 CE): The 17-year-old Umayyad general conquered Sindh — the first permanent Muslim foothold in South Asia. Often called the 'gateway of Islam to India'. The Chach Nama is the primary historical source.",
    "Mahmud of Ghazni (998–1030): Launched 17 raids into the Indian subcontinent. His sack of the Somnath temple (1026) became iconic in both Islamic and Hindu historical memory. The plunder financed a brilliant court at Ghazni that included the poet Firdausi and the scholar al-Biruni.",
    "Ranjit Singh and the Sikh Empire (1799–1849): 'The Lion of the Punjab' unified the Sikh misls into a powerful kingdom with a modernised army trained by European officers. Controlled Punjab, Kashmir, Peshawar, and Multan. The empire collapsed after his death; the Anglo-Sikh Wars (1845–46, 1848–49) led to British annexation.",
    "Partition of India (1947): The British Indian Empire was divided into India and Pakistan. Approximately 10–20 million people were displaced in one of the largest mass migrations in history, with communal violence killing 200,000–2,000,000 people. Pakistan was created as a homeland for South Asian Muslims."
  ]
}
